obj_root_law_sections_36_content:
  string
  line `^1[36. Power to frame and publish lists of touts.--(1) Every High Court, District Judge,`
  line `Sessions Judge, District Magistrate and Presidency Magistrate, every Revenue -officer, not`
  line `being below the rank of a Collector of a district, and the Chief Judge of every Presidency`
  line `Small Cause Court (each as regards their or his own Court and the Courts, if any, subordinate`
  line `thereto) may frame and publish lists of persons proved to their or his satisfaction, ^2[or to the`
  line `satisfaction of any subordinate Court as provided in sub-section (2A)] by evidence of general`
  line `repute or otherwise, habitually to act as touts, and may, from time to time, alter and amend`
  line `such lists.`
  line
  line `^2[Explanation.--The passing of a resolution, declaring any person to be or not to be a`
  line `tout, by a majority of the members present at a meeting, specially convened for the purpose,`
  line `of an association of persons entitled to practise as legal practitioners in any Court or revenue -`
  line `office, shall be evidence of the general repute of such person for the purposes of this subsection.]`
  line
  line `(2) No person's name shall be included in any such list until he shall have had an`
  line `opportunity of showing cause against such inclusion.`
  line
  line `^2[(2A) Any authority empowered under sub-section (1) to frame and publish a list of`
  line `touts may send to any Court subordinate to such authority the names of any persons alleged`
  line `or suspected to be touts, and order that Court to hold an inquiry in regard to such persons;`
  line `and the subordinate Court shall thereupon hold an inquiry into the conduct of such persons`
  line `and, after giving each such parson an opportunity of showing cause as provided in sub -`
  line `section (2), shall report to the authority which has ordered the inquiry the name of each such`
  line `person who has been proved to the satisfaction of the subordinate Court to be a tout; and`
  line `that authority may include the name of any such person in the list of touts framed and`
  line `published by that authority.`
  line
  line `Provided that such authority shall hear any such person who, before his name has been`
  line `so included, appears before it and desires to be heard.]`
  line
  line `(3) A copy of every such list shall be kept hung up in every Court to which the same relates.`
  line
  line `(4) The Court or Judge may, by general or special order, exclude from the precincts of the Court any`
  line `person whose name is included in any such list.`
  line
  line `(5) Every person whose name is included in any such list shall be deemed to be`
  line `proclaimed as a tout within the meaning of section 13, clause ( e), and section 22, clause (d).`
  line
  line `^2[(6) Any person who acts as a tout whilst his name is included in any such list shall be`
  line `punishable with imprisonment which may extend to three months, or with fine which may`
  line `extend to five hundred rupees, or with both.]`
obj_root_law_sections_36_footnotes:
  string
  line `1. Subs. by Act 11 of 1896, s. 4, for section 36.`
  line
  line `2. Ins. by Act 15 of 1926, s. 3.`
